There are several ways to center a div both horizontally and vertically using CSS. Here are some of the most common and effective methods, along with explanations:

**1. Using Flexbox (Recommended for modern browsers)**

Flexbox is a powerful layout module that makes centering elements very straightforward.

```css
.center-div {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center; /* Centers horizontally */
  align-items: center;     /* Centers vertically */
  height: 100vh;           /* Example: Make the parent take up the full viewport height */
  /* You can also set a specific height for the parent */
}

/* Optional: Style the div itself */
.center-div > div {
  width: 200px;
  height: 150px;
  background-color: lightblue;
  text-align: center; /* To center text inside the div */
  line-height: 150px; /* To center text vertically inside the div */
}
```

**Explanation:**

*   `display: flex;`: This turns the parent element into a flex container.
*   `justify-content: center;`: This aligns flex items along the main axis (horizontally by default) to the center.
*   `align-items: center;`: This aligns flex items along the cross axis (vertically by default) to the center.
*   `height: 100vh;` (or a specific height): This is crucial for `align-items: center;` to work effectively. The parent element needs to have a defined height for vertical centering to be meaningful. `100vh` makes the parent take up the full height of the viewport.

**HTML Structure:**

```html
<div class="center-div">
  <div>
    This div is centered.
  </div>
</div>
```

**2. Using CSS Grid (Also recommended for modern browsers)**

CSS Grid is another powerful layout system that excels at two-dimensional layouts, including centering.

```css
.center-div {
  display: grid;
  place-items: center; /* Centers both horizontally and vertically */
  height: 100vh;      /* Example: Make the parent take up the full viewport height */
  /* You can also set a specific height for the parent */
}
